            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is put-call parity?</h2>
              <p>
                Put-call parity is a fundamental no-arbitrage relationship
                between European call and put options with the same strike price
                and expiration on the same underlying asset. It links option
                prices to the spot price, interest rates, and dividends.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Basic (no-dividend) put-call parity
                </p>
                <p>\[ C + K e^{-rT} = P + S \]</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li><strong>C</strong> = price of a European call option</li>
                  <li><strong>P</strong> = price of a European put option</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>S</strong> = current spot price of the underlying
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>K</strong> = strike price</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = risk-free interest rate (continuously
                    compounded)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>T</strong> = time to maturity in years</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Put-call parity with dividends / cost of carry
                </p>
                <p>\[ C + K e^{-rT} + D = P + S \]</p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  where <strong>D</strong> is the present value of dividends (or
                  net carry) paid by the underlying over the life of the option.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Rearranging the put-call parity formula</h2>
              <p>You can solve the parity equation for any unknown variable:</p>

              <h3>Solve for call price C</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">\[ C = P + S - K e^{-rT} - D \]</div>

              <h3>Solve for put price P</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">\[ P = C + K e^{-rT} + D - S \]</div>

              <h3>Forward price from options (synthetic forward)</h3>
              <p>
                The value of a synthetic forward position (long call + short
                put) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\[ F_0 = S - D + (C - P) \]</div>
              <p class="text-sm">
                For a frictionless market with perfect parity, this equals the
                theoretical forward price \( F_0 = S e^{(r-q)T} \) where \( q \)
                is the dividend yield.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use this put-call parity calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter market inputs</strong>: spot price S, strike K,
                  time to expiry T, risk-free rate r, and PV of dividends D (if
                  any).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter known option prices</strong>: type in the
                  observed call and/or put prices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose what to solve for</strong>: call, put,
                  synthetic forward, or parity gap.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate”</strong>: the tool computes the
                  discounted strike, both sides of the parity equation, and the
                  requested unknown.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interpret the parity gap</strong>: a large gap
                  suggests mispricing or an arbitrage opportunity, subject to
                  transaction costs and early exercise features.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Interpreting the parity gap and arbitrage direction</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator reports the difference between the left-hand side
                (LHS) and right-hand side (RHS) of the parity equation:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{Gap} = (C + K e^{-rT} + D) - (P + S) \]
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gap ≈ 0</strong>: prices are consistent with put-call
                  parity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gap &gt; 0</strong>: LHS is overpriced relative to
                  RHS. A classic strategy is to <em>sell</em> the expensive side
                  and <em>buy</em> the cheap side.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gap &lt; 0</strong>: RHS is overpriced; reverse the
                  trade.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm">
                In practice, you must also consider bid-ask spreads,
                commissions, margin requirements, and the fact that most listed
                options are American-style.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and practical notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Put-call parity holds exactly only for
                  <strong>European options</strong> without early exercise.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For <strong>American options</strong>, parity becomes an
                  inequality; early exercise of deep-in-the-money puts or calls
                  can break strict equality.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Dividends, borrow fees, and short-selling constraints can all
                  affect real-world arbitrage trades.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use this tool as a <strong>diagnostic</strong> for relative
                  pricing, not as a guarantee of risk-free profit.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you observe the following on a non-dividend-paying
                stock:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>S = 100</li>
                <li>K = 100</li>
                <li>T = 0.5 years</li>
                <li>r = 4% (0.04)</li>
                <li>D = 0</li>
                <li>P (put price) = 3.50</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( K e^{-rT} = 100 e^{-0.04 \cdot 0.5} \approx 100 e^{-0.02}
                  \approx 98.02 \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Fair call price from parity: \[ C = P + S - K e^{-rT} = 3.50 +
                  100 - 98.02 \approx 5.48 \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If the market call price is, say, 6.20, the call is richer than
                parity suggests by about 0.72. That difference might or might
                not be tradable after costs.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>
                Does put-call parity depend on a specific option pricing model?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. Put-call parity is a <strong>no-arbitrage identity</strong>,
                not a model like Black–Scholes. It must hold in any
                arbitrage-free market, regardless of volatility assumptions.
              </p>

              <h3>Why use continuous compounding (e<sup>rT</sup>)?</h3>
              <p>
                Continuous compounding is standard in derivatives pricing and
                simplifies the algebra. For short maturities and moderate rates,
                the difference from simple compounding is usually small.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for index options with dividends?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Estimate the present value of expected dividends over the
                option’s life (or use a dividend yield) and enter it as D. The
                calculator then uses the dividend-adjusted parity formula.
              </p>
